</table>
<p>Most scholars reconstruct clusters of <i>s-</i> with other consonants, and possibly other clusters as well, but this area remains unsettled.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBaxter1992222.E2.80.93232_19-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBaxter1992222.E2.80.93232-19"><span>[</span>18<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>In recent reconstructions, such as the widely accepted system of Baxter, the rest of the Old Chinese syllable consists of</p>
<ul>
<li>an optional medial <i>-r-</i>, <i>-j-</i> or the combination <i>-rj-</i></li>
<li>one of six <a href="/wiki/Vowel" title="Vowel">vowels</a>:</li>
</ul>
<table border="0" style="margin: 0em auto 0em auto; width: 120px; text-align: center;">
<tr>
<td>i</td>
<td rowspan="2">ə</td>
<td>u</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>e</td>
<td>o</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td></td>
<td>a</td>
<td></td>
</tr>
</table>
<ul>
<li>an optional coda, which could be a glide <i>-j</i> or <i>-w</i>, a nasal <i>-m</i>, <i>-n</i> or <i>-ŋ</i>, or a stop <i>-p</i>, <i>-t</i>, <i>-k</i> or <i>-kʷ</i>,</li>
<li>an optional post-coda <i>-ʔ</i> or <i>-s</i>.</li>
</ul>
<p>In such systems, Old Chinese has no <a href="/wiki/Tone_(linguistics)" title="Tone (linguistics)">tones</a>; the tonal distinctions of <a href="/wiki/Middle_Chinese" title="Middle Chinese">Middle Chinese</a> are believed to be conditioned by the Old Chinese post-codas.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBaxter1992178.E2.80.93185_20-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBaxter1992178.E2.80.93185-20"><span>[</span>19<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Old_Chinese&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Sources of evidence">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Sources_of_evidence">Sources of evidence</span></h3>
<p>Although the Chinese writing system is not alphabetic, comparison of words whose characters share a phonetic element (a phonetic series) yields much information about pronunciation. Often the characters in a phonetic series are still pronounced alike, as in the character 中 (<i>zhōng</i>, "middle"), which was adapted to write the words <i>chōng</i> ("pour", 沖) and <i>zhōng</i> ("loyal", 忠).<sup id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21"><span>[</span>20<span>]</span></a></sup> In other cases the words in a phonetic series have very different sounds in any known variety of Chinese, but are assumed to have been similar at the time the characters were chosen.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman198843.E2.80.9344_22-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman198843.E2.80.9344-22"><span>[</span>21<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Gu_yanwu.jpg" class="image"><img alt="A Qing dynasty scholar in traditional dress" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4e/Gu_yanwu.jpg/170px-Gu_yanwu.jpg" width="170" height="246" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Gu_yanwu.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="http://bits.wikimedia.org/skins-1.17/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Gu_Yanwu" title="Gu Yanwu">Gu Yanwu</a>, who began the systematic study of <a href="/wiki/Shijing" title="Shijing" class="mw-redirect">Shijing</a> rhymes</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Another source is the rhyming practice of the <i><a href="/wiki/Shijing" title="Shijing" class="mw-redirect">Shijing</a></i>, a collection of songs and poetry compiled in the 6th century BCE. Again some of these lines still rhyme today, but many do not, a fact that was attributed to lax rhyming practice until the late-<a href="/wiki/Ming_Dynasty" title="Ming Dynasty">Ming Dynasty</a> scholar <a href="/wiki/Chen_Di" title="Chen Di">Chen Di</a> argued that a former consistency had been obscured by <a href="/wiki/Sound_change" title="Sound change">sound change</a>. The systematic study of these rhymes began in the 17th century, when <a href="/wiki/Gu_Yanwu" title="Gu Yanwu">Gu Yanwu</a> divided them into ten <a href="/wiki/Syllable_rime" title="Syllable rime">rhyme</a> groups (韻部 <i>yùnbù</i>), which were subsequently refined by other Qing scholars, culminating in a standard set of 31 rhyme groups in the 1930s. One of these scholars, <a href="/wiki/Duan_Yucai" title="Duan Yucai">Duan Yucai</a>, stated the important principle that characters in the same phonetic series would be in the same rhyme group, making it possible to assign rhyme groups to almost all characters.<sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23"><span>[</span>22<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>The phonetic series and rhyme groups have been compared with the phonological system of the <i><a href="/wiki/Qieyun" title="Qieyun">Qieyun</a></i>, a <a href="/wiki/Rhyme_dictionary" title="Rhyme dictionary" class="mw-redirect">rhyme dictionary</a> published in 601, with many revisions and expansions over the following centuries. These dictionaries indicated pronunciation by dividing a <a href="/wiki/Syllable" title="Syllable">syllable</a> into an initial consonant and the rest, called the final. According to its preface, the <i>Qieyun</i> did not reflect a single contemporary dialect, but incorporated distinctions made in different parts of China at the time (a <a href="/wiki/Diasystem" title="Diasystem">diasystem</a>). The term "Early Middle Chinese" conventionally refers to this system. <a href="/wiki/Rhyme_table" title="Rhyme table" class="mw-redirect">Rhyme tables</a> from the <a href="/wiki/Song_Dynasty" title="Song Dynasty">Song Dynasty</a> contain a sophisticated <a href="/wiki/Distinctive_feature" title="Distinctive feature">feature</a> analysis of the <i>Qieyun</i> initials and finals, though not a full <a href="/wiki/Phonemic" title="Phonemic" class="mw-redirect">phonemic</a> analysis. Moreover they were influenced by the different pronunciations of that later period. Scholars have attempted to determine the phonetic content of the various distinctions by comparing them with modern varieties and <a href="/wiki/Sinoxenic" title="Sinoxenic" class="mw-redirect">Sinoxenic</a> pronunciations, but many details regarding the finals are still disputed.<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24"><span>[</span>23<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>In 1940, the Swedish sinologist <a href="/wiki/Bernhard_Karlgren" title="Bernhard Karlgren">Bernhard Karlgren</a> published the first complete reconstruction of Old Chinese in a dictionary called the <i>Grammata Serica</i>, in which characters are arranged by phonetic series within rhyme groups. The 1957 revision <i><a href="/wiki/Grammata_Serica_Recensa" title="Grammata Serica Recensa">Grammata Serica Recensa</a></i> remains a standard reference, even though Karlgren's reconstructions have been superseded by those of <a href="/wiki/Wang_Li_(linguist)" title="Wang Li (linguist)">Wang Li</a>, <a href="/wiki/Edwin_G._Pulleyblank" title="Edwin G. Pulleyblank">E. G. Pulleyblank</a>, <a href="/wiki/Li_Fang-Kuei" title="Li Fang-Kuei">Li Fang-Kuei</a> and <a href="/wiki/William_H._Baxter" title="William H. Baxter">William Baxter</a>, among others.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESchuessler2009ix_25-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTESchuessler2009ix-25"><span>[</span>24<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Old_Chinese&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Initials">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Initials">Initials</span></h3>
<p>The reconstruction of the initial consonants of Old Chinese is based on comparison of phonetic series with the pronunciations given in the <i>Qieyun</i>, which distinguishes the following initials, each traditionally named with an exemplary word:<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBaxter199245.E2.80.9359_26-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBaxter199245.E2.80.9359-26"><span>[</span>25<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<table class="wikitable" style="margin: 1em auto 1em auto;">
<caption>Initials of Early Middle Chinese</caption>
