<th scope="row"><a href="/wiki/Alveolo-palatal_consonant" title="Alveolo-palatal consonant">Palatal sibilants</a><sup id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34"><span>[</span>n 6<span>]</span></a></sup></th>
<td><span class="explain" title="zhāng">章</span> <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[tɕ]</span></td>
<td><span class="explain" title="chāng">昌</span> <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[tɕʰ]</span></td>
<td><span class="explain" title="chán">禪</span> <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[dʑ]</span><sup id="cite_ref-dzr_36-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-dzr-36"><span>[</span>n 7<span>]</span></a></sup></td>
<td><span class="explain" title="rì">日</span> <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[ȵ]</span></td>
<td><span class="explain" title="shū">書</span> <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[ɕ]</span></td>
<td><span class="explain" title="chuán">船</span> <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[ʑ]</span><sup id="cite_ref-dzr_36-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-dzr-36"><span>[</span>n 7<span>]</span></a></sup></td>
<td align="center"><span class="explain" title="yǐ">以</span> <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[j]</span><sup id="cite_ref-palatal_38-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-palatal-38"><span>[</span>n 8<span>]</span></a></sup></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th scope="row"><span class="explain" title="牙音 yáyīn">牙</span></th>
<th scope="row"><a href="/wiki/Velar_consonant" title="Velar consonant">Velars</a></th>
<td><span class="explain" title="jiàn">見</span> <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[k]</span></td>
<td><span class="explain" title="xī">溪</span> <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[kʰ]</span></td>
<td><span class="explain" title="qún">群</span> <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[ɡ]</span></td>
<td><span class="explain" title="yí">疑</span> <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[ŋ]</span></td>
<td></td>
<td></td>
<td></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th scope="row"><span class="explain" title="喉音 hóuyīn">喉</span></th>
<th scope="row"><a href="/wiki/Laryngeal_consonant" title="Laryngeal consonant">Laryngeals</a><sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40"><span>[</span>n 9<span>]</span></a></sup></th>
<td><span class="explain" title="yǐng">影</span> <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[ʔ]</span></td>
<td></td>
<td></td>
<td></td>
<td><span class="explain" title="xiǎo">曉</span> <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[x]</span></td>
<td><span class="explain" title="xiá">匣</span>/<span class="explain" title="yún">云</span> <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[ɣ]</span><sup id="cite_ref-palatal_38-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-palatal-38"><span>[</span>n 8<span>]</span></a></sup></td>
<td></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>The Qing philologist Qian Daxin discovered that the Middle Chinese dental and retroflex stop series were not distinguished in Old Chinese.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman198844_41-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman198844-41"><span>[</span>33<span>]</span></a></sup> The resulting inventory of 32 initials (omitting the rare initial <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[ʐ]</span>) is still used by some scholars within China, such as <a href="/wiki/He_Jiuying" title="He Jiuying">He Jiuying</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHe199169.E2.80.9375_42-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHe199169.E2.80.9375-42"><span>[</span>34<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h4><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Old_Chinese&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Evidence from phonetic series">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Evidence_from_phonetic_series">Evidence from phonetic series</span></h4>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Shuowen.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Cover page with the name of the book in small seal characters" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7c/Shuowen.jpg/170px-Shuowen.jpg" width="170" height="273" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Shuowen.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="http://bits.wikimedia.org/skins-1.17/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
The cover of a modern reprint of a <a href="/wiki/Song_Dynasty" title="Song Dynasty">Song Dynasty</a> copy of the <i>Shuowen Jiezi</i>, an early source on the structure of characters</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>A key principle, first proposed by Karlgren, holds that the initials of words written with the same phonetic component had a common <a href="/wiki/Point_of_articulation" title="Point of articulation" class="mw-redirect">point of articulation</a> in Old Chinese. For example, since Middle Chinese dentals, retroflex stops and palatal sibilants occur together in phonetic series, they are traced to a single Old Chinese dental series, with the retroflex stops and palatal sibilants conditioned by Old Chinese medials *<i>-r-</i> and *<i>-j-</i> respectively. Similarly the freely interchangeable Middle Chinese dental sibilants and retroflex sibilants are traced to a single Old Chinese sibilant series, with the retroflex sibilants conditioned by the Old Chinese medial *<i>-r-</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-43"><span>[</span>35<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>However there are several cases where quite different Middle Chinese initials appear together in a phonetic series. Karlgren and subsequent workers have proposed either additional Old Chinese consonants or initial consonant clusters in such cases.</p>
<p>It is proposed that the *<i>-r-</i> medial could occur after labials and velars, complementing the instances proposed as sources of Middle Chinese retroflex dentals and sibilants, to account for such connections as<sup id="cite_ref-44" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44"><span>[</span>36<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46"><span>[</span>n 10<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48"><span>[</span>n 11<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<ul>
<li>變 <i>pjän-</i> (&lt; *<i>pr-</i>) "change" and "䜌 <i>luân</i> (&lt; *<i>br-</i>) "harness bells"<sup id="cite_ref-49" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49"><span>[</span>39<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>監 <i>kam</i> (&lt; *<i>kr-</i>) "look at" and 藍 <i>lâm</i> (&lt; *<i>gr-</i>) "indigo"<sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50"><span>[</span>40<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
</ul>
<p>Voiced and voiceless laterals *<i>l-</i> and *<i>l̥-</i> are proposed to account for series such as</p>
<ul>
<li>兌 <i>dwâi-</i> (&lt; *<i>l-</i>) "glad", 悅 <i>jwät</i> (&lt; *<i>lj-</i>) "pleased", 脫 <i>thuât</i> (&lt; *<i>l̥-</i>) "peel off" and 說 <i>śjwät</i> (&lt; OC <i>l̥j-</i>) "speak"<sup id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-51"><span>[</span>41<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-52" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-52"><span>[</span>n 12<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
</ul>
<p>These initials have no connection with Middle Chinese <i>l-</i>, which is believed to derive from an Old Chinese *<i>-r-</i> medial as discussed above.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBaxter1992197_53-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBaxter1992197-53"><span>[</span>42<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Voiceless nasal initials *<i>m̥-</i>, *<i>n̥-</i> and *<i>ŋ̊-</i> are proposed (following <a href="/w/index.php?title=Dong_Tonghe&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Dong Tonghe (page does not exist)">Dong Tonghe</a> and <a href="/wiki/Edwin_Pulleyblank" title="Edwin Pulleyblank" class="mw-redirect">Edwin Pulleyblank</a>) in series such as<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPulleyblank196292_54-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPulleyblank196292-54"><span>[</span>43<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<ul>
<li>墨 <i>mək</i> "ink" and 黑 <i>xək</i> (&lt; *<i>m̥-</i>) "black"<sup id="cite_ref-55" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-55"><span>[</span>44<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>難 <i>nân</i> "difficult" and 灘 <i>thân</i> (&lt; *<i>n̥-</i>) "foreshore"<sup id="cite_ref-56" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-56"><span>[</span>45<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>虐 <i>ngjak</i> "cruel" and 謔 <i>xjak</i> (&lt; *<i>ŋ̊-</i>) "to ridicule"<sup id="cite_ref-57" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-57"><span>[</span>46<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
</ul>
<p>Clusters *<i>sn-</i> and so on are proposed (following Karlgren) for alternations of Middle Chinese nasals and <i>s-</i> such as</p>
<ul>
<li>如 <i>ńźjwo</i> (&lt; *<i>nj-</i>) "resemble" and 絮 <i>sjwo-</i> (&lt; *<i>snj-</i>) "raw silk"<sup id="cite_ref-58" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-58"><span>[</span>47<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
</ul>
<p>Other cluster initials, including *<i>s</i> with stops or stops with *<i>l</i>, have been proposed but their existence and nature remains an open question.<sup id="cite_ref-59" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-59"><span>[</span>48<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h4><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Old_Chinese&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Back initials">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Back_initials">Back initials</span></h4>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Song_Dynasty" title="Song Dynasty">Song Dynasty</a> rhyme tables classified <i>Qieyun</i> syllables as either "open" (<i>kāi</i> 開) or "closed" (<i>hé</i> 合), the latter interpreted as denoting a medial <i>-w-</i> or lip rounding.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman198832_60-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman198832-60"><span>[</span>49<span>]</span></a></sup> This medial was unevenly distributed, being distinctive only after velar and laryngeal initials or before <i>-ai</i>, <i>-an</i> or <i>-at</i>. This is taken (following Sergei Yakhontov) to indicate that Old Chinese had <a href="/wiki/Labiovelar_consonant" title="Labiovelar consonant">labiovelar</a> and labiolaryngeal initials but no corresponding medial. The remaining occurrences of Middle Chinese <i>-w-</i> are believed to result from <a href="/wiki/Vowel_breaking" title="Vowel breaking">breaking</a> of a back vowel before these codas (see <a href="#Vowels">Vowels</a> below).<sup id="cite_ref-61" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-61"><span>[</span>50<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Pan Wuyun has proposed a revision of the above scheme to account for the fact that words with Middle Chinese laryngeal initials occurred together in phonetic series, unlike dental stops and fricatives, which were usually separated. Instead of the glottal stop initial *<i>ʔ-</i> and fricatives *<i>h-</i> and *<i>ɦ-</i>, he proposed <a href="/wiki/Uvular_stop" title="Uvular stop">uvular stops</a> *<i>q-</i>, *<i>qʰ-</i> and *<i>ɢ-</i>, and similarly labio-uvular stops *<i>qʷ-</i>, *<i>qʷʰ-</i> and *<i>ɢʷ-</i> in place of *<i>ʔʷ-</i>, *<i>hʷ-</i> and *<i>w-</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESagart2007_62-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTESagart2007-62"><span>[</span>51<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h4><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Old_Chinese&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Evidence from Min Chinese">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Evidence_from_Min_Chinese">Evidence from Min Chinese</span></h4>
<p>Modern <a href="/wiki/Min_Chinese" title="Min Chinese">Min Chinese</a> varieties, particularly inland ones, show reflexes of distinctions not reflected in Middle Chinese. For example, the following dental initials have been identified in reconstructed proto-Min, and other points of articulation show similar distinctions within stops and nasals.<sup id="cite_ref-63" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-63"><span>[</span>52<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<table class="wikitable" style="margin: 1em auto 1em auto; text-align: center">
<tr>
<th></th>
<th colspan="3">Voiceless stops</th>
<th colspan="3">Voiced stops</th>
<th colspan="2">Nasals</th>
<th colspan="2">Laterals</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<th>Example word</th>
<td><a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E5%96%AE" class="extiw" title="wikt:單">單</a></td>
<td><a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E5%A4%A9" class="extiw" title="wikt:天">天</a></td>
<td><a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E8%BD%89" class="extiw" title="wikt:轉">轉</a></td>
<td><a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E7%9B%B4" class="extiw" title="wikt:直">直</a></td>
<td><a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E9%A0%AD" class="extiw" title="wikt:頭">頭</a></td>
<td><a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E9%95%B7" class="extiw" title="wikt:長">長</a></td>
<td><a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E5%8D%97" class="extiw" title="wikt:南">南</a></td>
