<td>*Kr-</td>
<td>*Krj-</td>
<td>*Kj-</td>
<td>*K-</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>*Kʷ-</td>
<td>*Kʷr-</td>
<td>*Kʷrj-</td>
<td>*Kʷj-</td>
<td>*Kʷ-</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>Here P, T, TS, K and Kʷ stand for consonant classes in Old Chinese. Columns III-3 and III-4 represent the <i><a href="/wiki/Ch%C3%B3ngni%C7%94" title="Chóngniǔ" class="mw-redirect">chóngniǔ</a></i> distinction among some syllables with division-III finals, which are placed in rows 3 or 4 of the Song Dynasty <a href="/wiki/Rhyme_table" title="Rhyme table" class="mw-redirect">rhyme tables</a>. The two are generally identical in modern Chinese varieties, but <a href="/wiki/Sinoxenic" title="Sinoxenic" class="mw-redirect">Sinoxenic</a> forms often have a palatal element for III-4 but not III-3. Some scholars attribute this distinction to the medial and others to the vowel.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBaxter199263.2C_75.E2.80.9379.2C_282.E2.80.93287_71-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBaxter199263.2C_75.E2.80.9379.2C_282.E2.80.93287-71"><span>[</span>58<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-73" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-73"><span>[</span>n 15<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Baxter's account departs from the earlier reconstruction of Li Fang-Kuei in its treatment of *<i>-j-</i> and *<i>-rj-</i> after labial and guttural initials. Li proposed *<i>Krj-</i> as the source of palatal initials occurring in phonetic series with velars or laryngeals, found no evidence for *<i>Prj-</i>, and attributed the <i>chongniu</i> distinction to the vowel. Following proposals by Pulleyblank, Baxter explains <i>chongniu</i> using *<i>-rj-</i> and postulates that plain velars and laryngeals were palatalized when followed by both *<i>-j-</i> (but not *<i>-rj-</i>) and a front vowel. However a significant number of palatalizations are not explained by this rule.<sup id="cite_ref-74" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-74"><span>[</span>60<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h4><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Old_Chinese&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Reconsidering the palatal medial">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Reconsidering_the_palatal_medial">Reconsidering the palatal medial</span></h4>
<p>A number of scholars have suggested that the medial <i>-j-</i> of Middle Chinese, which is reconstructed in over half of the syllables of the <i>Qieyun</i>, was a secondary development not present in Old Chinese. Evidence includes the use of such syllables to transcribe foreign words lacking any such medial, the lack of the medial in Tibeto-Burman cognates and modern Min reflexes, and the fact that it is ignored in phonetic series.<sup id="cite_ref-75" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-75"><span>[</span>61<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Nonetheless, scholars agree that the difference reflects a real phonological distinction of some sort, which (following Pulleyblank) is often described noncommittally as a distinction between type A and B syllables (the latter having division-III finals), using a variety of notations.<sup id="cite_ref-76" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-76"><span>[</span>62<span>]</span></a></sup> The distinguishing feature has been variously ascribed to:</p>
<ul>
<li>the presence or absence of a prefix. Jakhontov held that type B reflected a prefix *<i>d-</i>,<sup id="cite_ref-77" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-77"><span>[</span>63<span>]</span></a></sup> while Ferlus suggested that type A arose from an unstressed prefix *<i>Cə-</i> (a <a href="/wiki/Minor_syllable" title="Minor syllable">minor syllable</a>), which conditioned syllabic <a href="/wiki/Tenseness" title="Tenseness">tenseness</a> contrasting with laxness in type B syllables.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFerlus2004305.E2.80.93307_78-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEFerlus2004305.E2.80.93307-78"><span>[</span>64<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>a length distinction of the main vowel. Pulleyblank initially proposed that type B syllables had longer vowels,<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPulleyblank1992379_79-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPulleyblank1992379-79"><span>[</span>65<span>]</span></a></sup> but Starostin and Zhengzhang later proposed long vowels for type A and short vowels for type B.<sup id="cite_ref-80" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-80"><span>[</span>66<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>a <a href="/wiki/Prosodic" title="Prosodic" class="mw-redirect">prosodic</a> distinction, as later proposed by Pulleyblank.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPulleyblank1992379_79-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPulleyblank1992379-79"><span>[</span>65<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Pharyngealization" title="Pharyngealization">pharyngealization</a> of the initial consonant. Norman suggested that the more numerous type B syllables (which he called type C) were in fact <a href="/wiki/Markedness" title="Markedness">unmarked</a> in Old Chinese. Instead, he proposed that the remaining syllables were marked either by retroflexion (the *<i>-r-</i> medial) or pharyngealization, either of which prevented palatalization in Middle Chinese.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman1994_81-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman1994-81"><span>[</span>67<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
</ul>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Old_Chinese&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Vowels">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Vowels">Vowels</span></h3>
<p>Reconstruction of the finals has proceeded by comparing the rhyme groups derived from the <i>Shijing</i> with the finals of Middle Chinese as described by the rhyme dictionaries.</p>
<p>As described in the previous section, the vocalic contrasts of many finals (those in divisions II and III of the rhyme tables) are now thought to derive from Old Chinese medials *<i>-r-</i> and *<i>-j-</i>, with the remaining Middle Chinese finals (divisions I and IV) containing pure vowels. The following table lists the names of the 31 traditional rhyme groups, with their Middle Chinese reflexes in these divisions and their postulated Old Chinese vowels in the systems of Li Fang-Kuei and William Baxter:<sup id="cite_ref-82" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-82"><span>[</span>68<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
