<td><i>khyi</i></td>
<td><i>khwe</i> &lt; *<i>khuy</i></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>Some progress has been made on the sound correspondences between Chinese and <a href="/wiki/Tibeto-Burman_languages" title="Tibeto-Burman languages">Tibeto-Burman</a>, though hampered by the difficulty of reconstruction on both sides.<sup id="cite_ref-106" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-106"><span>[</span>91<span>]</span></a></sup> The initial systems are similar, except that <a href="/wiki/Proto-Tibeto-Burman" title="Proto-Tibeto-Burman" class="mw-redirect">Proto-Tibeto-Burman</a> has no aspiration distinction on initial stops and affricates, which is believed to be a Chinese innovation arising from earlier prefixes.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESchuessler200758.E2.80.9361_107-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTESchuessler200758.E2.80.9361-107"><span>[</span>92<span>]</span></a></sup> Proto-Sino-Tibetan is reconstructed with a six-vowel system as in recent reconstructions of Old Chinese, with Tibeto-Burman distinguished by the merger of the mid-central vowel *<i>-ə-</i> with *<i>-a-</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-108" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-108"><span>[</span>93<span>]</span></a></sup> The other vowels are preserved by both, with some alternation between *<i>-e-</i> and *<i>-i-</i>, and between *<i>-o-</i> and *<i>-u-</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESchuessler2007110.E2.80.93117_109-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTESchuessler2007110.E2.80.93117-109"><span>[</span>94<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Old_Chinese&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: Loanwords">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Loanwords">Loanwords</span></h3>
<p>The expansion of Chinese civilization has obliterated almost all traces of the languages spoken by the neighbours of the Chinese in pre-historic times. It is possible that these languages were the source of some of the many Chinese words whose origins are still unknown, but only a few glimpses remain.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman198816.E2.80.9317_110-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman198816.E2.80.9317-110"><span>[</span>95<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Jerry Norman and Mei Tsu-lin have identified a stratum of early <a href="/wiki/Austroasiatic" title="Austroasiatic" class="mw-redirect">Austroasiatic</a> loanwords in Old Chinese, possibly from the peoples known to ancient Chinese as the <a href="/wiki/Baiyue" title="Baiyue">Yue</a>, and perhaps even the <a href="/wiki/Dongyi" title="Dongyi">Yi</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPulleyblank1996b44.E2.80.9345_111-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPulleyblank1996b44.E2.80.9345-111"><span>[</span>96<span>]</span></a></sup> For example, the early Chinese name *<i>kroŋ</i> (<a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E6%B1%9F" class="extiw" title="wikt:江">江</a> <i>jiāng</i>) for the <a href="/wiki/Yangtze" title="Yangtze" class="mw-redirect">Yangtze</a> was later extended to a general word for "river" in south China. Norman and Mei suggest that the word is cognate with <a href="/wiki/Vietnamese_language" title="Vietnamese language">Vietnamese</a> <i>sông</i> (from *<i>krong</i>) and <a href="/wiki/Mon_language" title="Mon language">Mon</a> <i>kruŋ</i> "river".<sup id="cite_ref-112" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-112"><span>[</span>97<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Haudricourt and Strecker have proposed a number of borrowings from <a href="/wiki/Miao-Yao_languages" title="Miao-Yao languages" class="mw-redirect">Miao-Yao languages</a>, including terms related to <a href="/wiki/Rice" title="Rice">rice</a> cultivation, which began in the middle Yangtze valley:</p>
<ul>
<li>*<i>ʔjaŋ</i> (<a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E7%A7%A7" class="extiw" title="wikt:秧">秧</a> <i>yāng</i>) "rice seedling" from proto-Miao-Yao *<i>jaŋ</i></li>
<li>*<i>luʔ</i> (<a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E7%A8%BB" class="extiw" title="wikt:稻">稻</a> <i>dào</i>) "unhulled rice" from proto-Miao-Yao *<i>mblau</i><sup>A</sup><sup id="cite_ref-113" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-113"><span>[</span>98<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
</ul>
<p>Other words are believed to have been borrowed from languages to the south of the Chinese area, but it is not clear which was the original source, e.g.</p>
<ul>
<li>*<i>zjaŋʔ</i> (<a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E8%B1%A1" class="extiw" title="wikt:象">象</a> <i>xiàng</i>) "elephant" can be compared with Mon <i>coiŋ</i>, proto-<a href="/wiki/Tai_language" title="Tai language" class="mw-redirect">Tai</a> *<i>jaŋ<sup>C</sup></i> and Burmese <i>chaŋ</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-114" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-114"><span>[</span>99<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>*<i>ke</i> (<a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E9%9B%9E" class="extiw" title="wikt:雞">雞</a> <i>jī</i>) "chicken" versus proto-Tai *<i>kəi<sup>B</sup></i> proto-Miao-Yao *<i>kai</i> and proto-<a href="/wiki/Vietic_languages" title="Vietic languages">Viet-Muong</a> *<i>r-ka</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-115" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-115"><span>[</span>100<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
</ul>
<p>In ancient times, the <a href="/wiki/Tarim_basin" title="Tarim basin" class="mw-redirect">Tarim basin</a> was occupied by speakers of <a href="/wiki/Indo-European" title="Indo-European" class="mw-redirect">Indo-European</a> <a href="/wiki/Tocharian_languages" title="Tocharian languages">Tocharian languages</a>, the source of *<i>mjit</i> (<a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E8%9C%9C" class="extiw" title="wikt:蜜">蜜</a> <i>mì</i>) "honey", from Proto-Tocharian *<i>mjət</i> (cognate with English "<a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/mead" class="extiw" title="wikt:mead">mead</a>").<sup id="cite_ref-116" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-116"><span>[</span>101<span>]</span></a></sup> The surviving northern neighbours of Chinese, the <a href="/wiki/Altaic_language" title="Altaic language" class="mw-redirect">Altaic languages</a>, contributed such words as *<i>dok</i> (<a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E7%8A%A2" class="extiw" title="wikt:犢">犢</a> <i>dú</i>) "calf" – compare <a href="/wiki/Mongolian_language" title="Mongolian language">Mongolian</a> <i>tuɣul</i> and <a href="/wiki/Manchu_language" title="Manchu language">Manchu</a> <i>tukšan</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-117" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-117"><span>[</span>102<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Old_Chinese&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: Word formation">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Word_formation">Word formation</span></h3>
<p>Many students of Chinese have noted "word families", words with related meanings and variant pronunciations, sometimes but not always written using the same character. A common case is "derivation by tone change", in which words in the departing tone appear to be derived from words in other tones. If Haudricourt's theory of the origin of the departing tone is accepted, these derivations can be interpreted as a <i>-s</i> suffix. As Tibetan has a similar suffix, it may be inherited from Sino-Tibetan.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBaxter1992315.E2.80.93317_118-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBaxter1992315.E2.80.93317-118"><span>[</span>103<span>]</span></a></sup> Examples include:</p>
<ul>
<li>*<i>dzjin</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E7%9B%A1" class="extiw" title="wikt:盡">盡</a> "to exhaust" and *<i>dzjins</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E7%87%BC" class="extiw" title="wikt:燼">燼</a> "exhausted, consumed"<sup id="cite_ref-119" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-119"><span>[</span>104<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>*<i>kit</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E7%B5%90" class="extiw" title="wikt:結">結</a> "to tie" and *<i>kits</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E9%AB%BB" class="extiw" title="wikt:髻">髻</a> "hair-knot"<sup id="cite_ref-120" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-120"><span>[</span>105<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>*<i>nup</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E7%B4%8D" class="extiw" title="wikt:納">納</a> "to bring in" and *<i>nuts</i> &lt; *<i>nups</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E5%85%A7" class="extiw" title="wikt:內">內</a> "inside"<sup id="cite_ref-121" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-121"><span>[</span>106<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>*<i>tjək</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E7%B9%94" class="extiw" title="wikt:織">織</a> "to weave" and *<i>tjəks</i> 織 "silk cloth" (compare Written Tibetan '<i>thag</i> "to weave" and <i>thags</i> "woven, cloth")<sup id="cite_ref-122" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-122"><span>[</span>107<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
</ul>
<p>Another alternation involves transitive verbs with an unvoiced initial and passive or stative verbs with a voiced initial, possibly due to a voiced prefix:<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESchuessler200749_123-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTESchuessler200749-123"><span>[</span>108<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<ul>
<li>*<i>trjang</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E5%BC%B5" class="extiw" title="wikt:張">張</a> "to stretch" and *<i>drjang</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E9%95%B7" class="extiw" title="wikt:長">長</a> "long"<sup id="cite_ref-124" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-124"><span>[</span>109<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>*<i>kens</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E8%A6%8B" class="extiw" title="wikt:見">見</a> "to see" and *<i>gens</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E7%8F%BE" class="extiw" title="wikt:現">現</a> "to appear"<sup id="cite_ref-125" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-125"><span>[</span>110<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>*<i>kraw</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E4%BA%A4" class="extiw" title="wikt:交">交</a> "to mix" and *<i>graw</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E6%AE%BD" class="extiw" title="wikt:殽">殽</a> "mixed, confused"<sup id="cite_ref-126" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-126"><span>[</span>111<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
</ul>
<p>Several other affixes have been proposed.<sup id="cite_ref-127" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-127"><span>[</span>112<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>During the Western Zhou period many new bisyllabic words entered the language. Many words, particularly expressive adjectives and adverbs, were formed by varieties of <a href="/wiki/Reduplication" title="Reduplication">reduplication</a>:<sup id="cite_ref-Norman:reduplication_128-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Norman:reduplication-128"><span>[</span>113<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<ul>
<li>full reduplication, in which the syllable is repeated, as in *<i>ʔjuj-ʔjuj</i> (威威 <i>wēiwēi</i>) "tall and grand" and *<i>ljo-ljo</i> (俞俞 <i>yúyú</i>) "happy and at ease".<sup id="cite_ref-Norman:reduplication_128-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Norman:reduplication-128"><span>[</span>113<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>rhyming semi-reduplication, in which only the final is repeated, as in *<i>ʔiwʔ-liwʔ</i> (窈宨 <i>yǎotiǎo</i>) "elegant, beautiful".<sup id="cite_ref-BS:reduplication_129-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-BS:reduplication-129"><span>[</span>114<span>]</span></a></sup> The initial of the second syllable is often *<i>l-</i> or *<i>r-</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESchuessler200724_130-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTESchuessler200724-130"><span>[</span>115<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>alliterative semi-reduplication, in which the initial is repeated, as in *<i>tshrjum-tshrjaj</i> (參差 "cēncī") "irregular, uneven".<sup id="cite_ref-BS:reduplication_129-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-BS:reduplication-129"><span>[</span>114<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>vowel alternation, especially of *<i>-e-</i> and *<i>-o-</i>, as in *<i>tshjek-tshjok</i> (刺促 <i>qìcù</i>) "busy" and *<i>greʔ-groʔ</i> (邂逅 <i>xièhòu</i>) "carefree and happy".<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBaxterSagart199865.E2.80.9366_131-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBaxterSagart199865.E2.80.9366-131"><span>[</span>116<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
</ul>
<p>Other words, especially nouns, were formed by <a href="/wiki/Compound_(linguistics)" title="Compound (linguistics)">compounding</a>, including:</p>
<ul>
<li>qualification of one noun by another (placed in front), as in *<i>mok-kwra</i> (木瓜 <i>mùguā</i>) "quince" (literally "tree-melon"), and *<i>trjung-njit</i> (中日 <i>zhōngrì</i>) "noon" (literally "middle-day").<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBaxterSagart199867_132-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBaxterSagart199867-132"><span>[</span>117<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>verb-object compounds, as in *<i>sjə-mraʔ</i> (司馬 <i>sīmǎ</i>) "master of the household" (literally "manage-horse"), and *<i>tsak-tshrek</i> (作册 <i>zuòcè</i>) "scribe" (literally "make-writing").<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBaxterSagart199868_133-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBaxterSagart199868-133"><span>[</span>118<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
</ul>
<p>However the components of compounds were not <a href="/wiki/Bound_morpheme" title="Bound morpheme">bound morphemes</a>: they could still be used separately.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman198886_134-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman198886-134"><span>[</span>119<span>]</span></a></sup> Over 30% of the vocabulary of the <i><a href="/wiki/Mencius_(book)" title="Mencius (book)">Mencius</a></i> is polysyllabic, including 9% proper names, but monosyllabic words occur more frequently, accounting for 80–90% of the text.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWilkinson200031.E2.80.9336_135-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEWilkinson200031.E2.80.9336-135"><span>[</span>120<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Old_Chinese&amp;action=edit&amp;section=17" title="Edit section: Grammar">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Grammar">Grammar</span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:%E6%B8%85%E5%8D%8E%E7%AE%80.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Photograph of strips of bamboo with vertical writing in an early Chinese seal script" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/%E6%B8%85%E5%8D%8E%E7%AE%80.jpg/170px-%E6%B8%85%E5%8D%8E%E7%AE%80.jpg" width="170" height="292" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:%E6%B8%85%E5%8D%8E%E7%AE%80.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="http://bits.wikimedia.org/skins-1.17/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Seal script on bamboo strips from the <a href="/wiki/Warring_States_Period" title="Warring States Period">Warring States Period</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="rellink boilerplate seealso">See also: <a href="/wiki/Classical_Chinese_grammar" title="Classical Chinese grammar">Classical Chinese grammar</a></div>
<p>Little is known of the grammar of the language of the Oracular and pre-Classical periods, as the texts are often of a ritual or formulaic nature, and much of their vocabulary has not been deciphered. In contrast, the rich literature of the <a href="/wiki/Warring_States_Period" title="Warring States Period">Warring States Period</a> has been extensively analysed.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHerforth200359_136-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHerforth200359-136"><span>[</span>121<span>]</span></a></sup> Having no <a href="/wiki/Inflection" title="Inflection">inflection</a>, Old Chinese was heavily reliant on word order, <a href="/wiki/Grammatical_particle" title="Grammatical particle">grammatical particles</a> and inherent <a href="/wiki/Word_class" title="Word class" class="mw-redirect">word classes</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-137" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-137"><span>[</span>122<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Old_Chinese&amp;action=edit&amp;section=18" title="Edit section: Word classes">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Word_classes">Word classes</span></h3>
<p>Classifying Old Chinese words is not always straightforward, as words were not marked for function, word classes overlapped, and words of one class could sometimes be used in roles normally reserved for a different class.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman198887.E2.80.9388_138-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman198887.E2.80.9388-138"><span>[</span>123<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Old Chinese <a href="/wiki/Noun" title="Noun">nouns</a> and <a href="/wiki/Pronoun" title="Pronoun">pronouns</a> did not indicate number or gender, but some <a href="/wiki/Personal_pronoun" title="Personal pronoun">personal pronouns</a> showed case distinctions:<sup id="cite_ref-139" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-139"><span>[</span>124<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<table class="wikitable" style="margin: 1em auto 1em auto; text-align: center;">
<tr>
<th></th>
<th>Possessive</th>
<th width="25%">Subject</th>
<th width="25%">Object</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<th rowspan="2">1st person</th>
<td colspan="3">*<i>ljaʔ</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E4%BA%88" class="extiw" title="wikt:予">予</a> / *<i>lja</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E4%BD%99" class="extiw" title="wikt:余">余</a> / *<i>ljə</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E5%8F%B0" class="extiw" title="wikt:台">台</a></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan="2">*<i>ŋa</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E5%90%BE" class="extiw" title="wikt:吾">吾</a></td>
<td>*<i>ŋajʔ</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E6%88%91" class="extiw" title="wikt:我">我</a></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th>2nd person</th>
<td colspan="3">*<i>njaʔ</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E6%B1%9D" class="extiw" title="wikt:汝">汝</a> / *<i>njəjʔ</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E7%88%BE" class="extiw" title="wikt:爾">爾</a> / *<i>njə</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E8%80%8C" class="extiw" title="wikt:而">而</a> / *<i>njak</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E8%8B%A5" class="extiw" title="wikt:若">若</a></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th>3rd person</th>
<td>*<i>gjə</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E5%85%B6" class="extiw" title="wikt:其">其</a></td>
<td bgcolor="#ccc"></td>
<td>*<i>tjə</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E4%B9%8B" class="extiw" title="wikt:之">之</a></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>In the post-Han period 我 and 其 came to be used as general first and third person pronouns respectively. The second person pronouns 汝 and 爾 continued to be used interchangeably until their replacement by the phonological variant <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E4%BD%A0" class="extiw" title="wikt:你">你</a> <i>nǐ</i> in the <a href="/wiki/Tang_dynasty" title="Tang dynasty" class="mw-redirect">Tang</a> period.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman1988117.E2.80.93118_140-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman1988117.E2.80.93118-140"><span>[</span>125<span>]</span></a></sup> There were also <a href="/wiki/Demonstrative_pronoun" title="Demonstrative pronoun" class="mw-redirect">demonstrative</a> and <a href="/wiki/Interrogative_pronoun" title="Interrogative pronoun" class="mw-redirect">interrogative pronouns</a>, but no <a href="/wiki/Indefinite_pronoun" title="Indefinite pronoun">indefinite pronouns</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman198890.E2.80.9391_141-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman198890.E2.80.9391-141"><span>[</span>126<span>]</span></a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Distributive_pronoun" title="Distributive pronoun">distributive pronouns</a> were formed with a *<i>-k</i> suffix:<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESchuessler200770_142-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTESchuessler200770-142"><span>[</span>127<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<ul>
<li>*<i>wək</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E6%88%96" class="extiw" title="wikt:或">或</a> "someone" from *<i>wjəʔ</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E6%9C%89" class="extiw" title="wikt:有">有</a> "there is"</li>
<li>*<i>mak</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E8%8E%AB" class="extiw" title="wikt:莫">莫</a> "no-one" from *<i>mja</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E7%84%A1" class="extiw" title="wikt:無">無</a> "there is no"</li>
<li>*<i>kak</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E5%90%84" class="extiw" title="wikt:各">各</a> "each" from *<i>kjaʔ</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E8%88%89" class="extiw" title="wikt:舉">舉</a> "all"</li>
</ul>
<p>As in the modern language, localizers (compass directions, "above", "inside" and the like) could be placed after nouns to indicate relative positions. They could also precede verbs to indicate the direction of the action.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman198891_143-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman198891-143"><span>[</span>128<span>]</span></a></sup> Nouns denoting times were another special class (time words); they usually preceded the subject to specify the time of an action.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman198891.2C_94_144-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman198891.2C_94-144"><span>[</span>129<span>]</span></a></sup> However the <a href="/wiki/Chinese_classifier" title="Chinese classifier">classifiers</a> so characteristic of Modern Chinese did not appear until the <a href="/wiki/Southern_and_Northern_Dynasties" title="Southern and Northern Dynasties">Southern and Northern Dynasties</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman1988115.E2.80.93116_145-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman1988115.E2.80.93116-145"><span>[</span>130<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Old Chinese <a href="/wiki/Verb" title="Verb">verbs</a>, like their modern counterparts, did not show tense or aspect; these could be clarified with adverbs or particles if required. Verbs could be <a href="/wiki/Transitive_verb" title="Transitive verb">transitive</a> or <a href="/wiki/Intransitive" title="Intransitive" class="mw-redirect">intransitive</a>. As in the modern language, <a href="/wiki/Adjective" title="Adjective">adjectives</a> were a special kind of intransitive verb, and a few transitive verbs could also function as <a href="/wiki/Modal_auxiliary" title="Modal auxiliary" class="mw-redirect">modal auxiliaries</a> or as <a href="/wiki/Preposition" title="Preposition" class="mw-redirect">prepositions</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman198891.E2.80.9394_146-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman198891.E2.80.9394-146"><span>[</span>131<span>]</span></a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Adverb" title="Adverb">Adverbs</a> described the scope of a statement or various temporal relationships.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman198894_147-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman198894-147"><span>[</span>132<span>]</span></a></sup> They included two families of negatives starting with *<i>p-</i> and *<i>m-</i>, such as *<i>pjə</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E4%B8%8D" class="extiw" title="wikt:不">不</a> and *<i>mja</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E7%84%A1" class="extiw" title="wikt:無">無</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman198897.E2.80.9398_148-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman198897.E2.80.9398-148"><span>[</span>133<span>]</span></a></sup> Modern northern varieties derive the usual negative from the first family, while southern varieties preserve the second.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESchuessler2007172.E2.80.93173.2C_518.E2.80.93519_149-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTESchuessler2007172.E2.80.93173.2C_518.E2.80.93519-149"><span>[</span>134<span>]</span></a></sup> The language had no adverbs of degree until late in the Classical period.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman198894.2C_127_150-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman198894.2C_127-150"><span>[</span>135<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p><a href="/wiki/Chinese_particle" title="Chinese particle" class="mw-redirect">Particles</a> were <a href="/wiki/Function_word" title="Function word">function words</a> serving a range of purposes. As in the modern language, there were sentence-final particles marking <a href="/wiki/Imperative_mood" title="Imperative mood">imperatives</a> and <a href="/wiki/Yes/no_question" title="Yes/no question" class="mw-redirect">yes/no questions</a>. Other sentence-final particles expressed a range of connotations, the most important being *<i>ljaj</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E4%B9%9F" class="extiw" title="wikt:也">也</a>, expressing static factuality, and *<i>ɦjəʔ</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E7%9F%A3" class="extiw" title="wikt:矣">矣</a>, implying a change. Other particles included the subordination marker *<i>tjə</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E4%B9%8B" class="extiw" title="wikt:之">之</a> and the nominalizing particles *<i>tjaʔ</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E8%80%85" class="extiw" title="wikt:者">者</a> (agent) and *<i>srjaʔ</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E6%89%80" class="extiw" title="wikt:所">所</a> (object).<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman198894.2C_98.E2.80.93100.2C_105.E2.80.93106_151-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman198894.2C_98.E2.80.93100.2C_105.E2.80.93106-151"><span>[</span>136<span>]</span></a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Conjunction_(grammar)" title="Conjunction (grammar)">Conjunctions</a> could join nouns or clauses.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman198894.2C_106.E2.80.93108_152-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman198894.2C_106.E2.80.93108-152"><span>[</span>137<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Old_Chinese&amp;action=edit&amp;section=19" title="Edit section: Sentence structure">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Sentence_structure">Sentence structure</span></h3>
<p>As with English and modern Chinese, Old Chinese sentences can be analysed as a <a href="/wiki/Subject_(grammar)" title="Subject (grammar)">subject</a> (a noun phrase, sometimes understood) followed by a <a href="/wiki/Predicate_(grammar)" title="Predicate (grammar)">predicate</a>, which could be of either nominal or verbal type.<sup id="cite_ref-153" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-153"><span>[</span>138<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Before the Classical period, nominal predicates consisted of a <a href="/wiki/Copula_(linguistics)" title="Copula (linguistics)">copular</a> particle *<i>wjij</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E6%83%9F" class="extiw" title="wikt:惟">惟</a> followed by a noun phrase:<sup id="cite_ref-154" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-154"><span>[</span>139<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<blockquote>
<table style="border: 1px solid darkgray; text-align: center;">
<tr>
<td>予</td>
<td>惟</td>
<td>小</td>
<td>子</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><i>*ljaʔ</i></td>
<td><i>wjij</i></td>
<td><i>sjewʔ</i></td>
<td><i>tsjəʔ</i></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>I</td>
<td>be</td>
<td>small</td>
<td>child</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>"I am a young person." (<i><a href="/wiki/Book_of_History" title="Book of History">Book of History</a></i> 27, 9)<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESchuessler200714_155-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTESchuessler200714-155"><span>[</span>140<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
</blockquote>
<p>The negated copula *<i>pjə-wjij</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E4%B8%8D" class="extiw" title="wikt:不">不</a><a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E6%83%9F" class="extiw" title="wikt:惟">惟</a> is attested in oracle bone inscriptions, and later fused as *<i>pjəj</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E9%9D%9E" class="extiw" title="wikt:非">非</a>. In the Classical period, nominal predicates were constructed with the sentence-final particle *<i>ljaj</i> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E4%B9%9F" class="extiw" title="wikt:也">也</a> instead of the copula 惟, but 非 was retained as the negative form, with which 也 was optional:<sup id="cite_ref-156" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-156"><span>[</span>141<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<blockquote>
<table style="border: 1px solid darkgray; text-align: center;">
<tr>
<td>其</td>
<td>至</td>
<td>爾</td>
<td>力</td>
<td>也</td>
<td>其</td>
<td>中</td>
<td>非</td>
<td>爾</td>
<td>力</td>
<td>也</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><i>*gjə</i></td>
<td><i>tjits</i></td>
<td><i>njəjʔ</i></td>
<td><i>C-rjək</i></td>
<td><i>ljajʔ</i></td>
<td><i>gjə</i></td>
<td><i>k-ljuŋ</i></td>
<td><i>pjəj</i></td>
<td><i>njəjʔ</i></td>
<td><i>C-rjək</i></td>
<td><i>ljajʔ</i></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>its</td>
<td>arrive</td>
<td>you</td>
<td>strength</td>
<td>P</td>
<td>its</td>
<td>centre</td>
<td>not</td>
<td>you</td>
<td>strength</td>
<td>P</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>(of shooting at a mark a hundred paces distant) "That you reach it is owing to your strength, but that you hit the mark is not owing to your strength." (<i><a href="/wiki/Mencius" title="Mencius">Mencius</a></i> 10.1/51/13)<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHerforth200360_157-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHerforth200360-157"><span>[</span>142<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
</blockquote>
<p>The copular verb <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E6%98%AF" class="extiw" title="wikt:是">是</a> (<i>shì</i>) of Literary and Modern Chinese dates from the Han period. In Old Chinese the word was a near <a href="/wiki/Demonstrative" title="Demonstrative">demonstrative</a> ("this").<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman1988125.E2.80.93126_158-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman1988125.E2.80.93126-158"><span>[</span>143<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>As in Modern Chinese, but unlike most Tibeto-Burman languages, the basic word order in a verbal sentence was <a href="/wiki/Subject-Verb-Object" title="Subject-Verb-Object" class="mw-redirect">Subject-Verb-Object</a>:<sup id="cite_ref-159" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-159"><span>[</span>144<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<blockquote>
<table style="border: 1px solid darkgray; text-align: center;">
<tr>
<td>孟</td>
<td>子</td>
<td>見</td>
<td>梁</td>
<td>惠</td>
<td>王</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><i>*mraŋs</i></td>
<td><i>tsəjʔ</i></td>
<td><i>kens</i></td>
<td><i>C-rjaŋ</i></td>
<td><i>wets</i></td>
<td><i>wjaŋ</i></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan="2">Mencius</td>
<td>see</td>
<td>Liang</td>
<td>Hui</td>
<td>king</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>"Mencius saw King Hui of Liang." (<i><a href="/wiki/Mencius" title="Mencius">Mencius</a></i> 1.1/1/3)<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPulleyblank1996a13_160-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPulleyblank1996a13-160"><span>[</span>145<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Besides inversions for emphasis, there were two exceptions to this rule: a pronoun object of a negated sentence or an interrogative pronoun object would be placed before the verb:<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPulleyblank1996a14_161-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPulleyblank1996a14-161"><span>[</span>146<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<blockquote>
<table style="border: 1px solid darkgray; text-align: center;">
<tr>
<td>歲</td>
<td>不</td>
<td>我</td>
<td>與</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><i>*swjats</i></td>
<td><i>pjə</i></td>
<td><i>ŋajʔ</i></td>
<td><i>ljaʔ</i></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>year</td>
<td>not</td>
<td>me</td>
<td>wait</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>"The years do not wait for us." (<i><a href="/wiki/Analects" title="Analects">Analects</a></i> 17.1/47/23)</p>
</blockquote>
<p>An additional noun phrase could be placed before the subject to serve as the <a href="/wiki/Topic_(linguistics)" title="Topic (linguistics)" class="mw-redirect">topic</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHerforth200366.E2.80.9367_162-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHerforth200366.E2.80.9367-162"><span>[</span>147<span>]</span></a></sup> As in the modern language, <a href="/wiki/Yes/no_question" title="Yes/no question" class="mw-redirect">yes/no questions</a> were formed by adding a sentence-final particle, and requests for information by substituting an <a href="/wiki/Interrogative_pronoun" title="Interrogative pronoun" class="mw-redirect">interrogative pronoun</a> for the requested element.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman198890.E2.80.9391.2C_98.E2.80.9399_163-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman198890.E2.80.9391.2C_98.E2.80.9399-163"><span>[</span>148<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>In general, Old Chinese modifiers preceded the words they modified. Thus <a href="/wiki/Relative_clause" title="Relative clause">relative clauses</a> were placed before the noun, usually marked by the particle <i>*tjə</i> 之 (in a role similar to Modern Chinese 的 <i>de</i>):<sup id="cite_ref-164" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-164"><span>[</span>149<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<blockquote>
<table style="border: 1px solid darkgray; text-align: center;">
<tr>
<td>不</td>
<td>忍</td>
<td>人</td>
<td>之</td>
<td>心</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><i>*pjə</i></td>
<td><i>njənʔ</i></td>
<td><i>njin</i></td>
<td><i>tjə</i></td>
<td><i>sjəm</i></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>not</td>
<td>endure</td>
<td>person</td>
<td>P</td>
<td>heart</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>"... the heart that cannot bear the afflictions of others." (<i><a href="/wiki/Mencius" title="Mencius">Mencius</a></i> 3.6/18/4)<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPulleyblank1996a62_165-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPulleyblank1996a62-165"><span>[</span>150<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
</blockquote>
<p>A common instance of this construction was adjectival modification, since the Old Chinese adjective was a type of verb, but 之 was usually omitted after monosyllabic adjectives.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPulleyblank1996a62_165-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPulleyblank1996a62-165"><span>[</span>150<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Similarly, adverbial modifiers, including various forms of negation, usually occurred before the verb.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman1988105_166-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman1988105-166"><span>[</span>151<span>]</span></a></sup> As in the modern language, time <a href="/wiki/Adjunct_(grammar)" title="Adjunct (grammar)">adjuncts</a> occurred either at the start of the sentence or before the verb, depending on their scope, while duration adjuncts were placed after the verb.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman1988103.E2.80.93104_167-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman1988103.E2.80.93104-167"><span>[</span>152<span>]</span></a></sup> Instrumental and place adjuncts were usually placed after the verb phrase. These later moved to a position before the verb, as in the modern language.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman1988103.2C_130.E2.80.93131_168-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman1988103.2C_130.E2.80.93131-168"><span>[</span>153<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Old_Chinese&amp;action=edit&amp;section=20" title="Edit section: Notes">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Notes">Notes</span></h2>
<div class="reflist" style="list-style-type: decimal;">
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-16"><b><a href="#cite_ref-16">^</a></b> Reconstructed Old Chinese forms follow <a href="#CITEREFBaxter1992">Baxter (1992)</a> with some graphical substitutions from his more recent work: "ə" for "ɨ"<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESchuessler2007122_15-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTESchuessler2007122-15"><span>[</span>16<span>]</span></a></sup> and consonants rendered according to IPA conventions.</li>
<li id="cite_note-18"><b><a href="#cite_ref-18">^</a></b> Baxter describes his reconstruction of the palatal initials as "especially tentative".<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBaxter1992203_17-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBaxter1992203-17"><span>[</span>17<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li id="cite_note-28"><b><a href="#cite_ref-28">^</a></b> The rhyme tables describe a later stage in which <a href="/wiki/Labiodental" title="Labiodental" class="mw-redirect">labiodental</a> fricatives were also distinguished.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBaxter199246.E2.80.9349_27-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBaxter199246.E2.80.9349-27"><span>[</span>26<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li id="cite_note-30"><b><a href="#cite_ref-30">^</a></b> It is not clear whether these had an <a href="/wiki/Alveolar_consonant" title="Alveolar consonant">alveolar</a> or <a href="/wiki/Dental_consonant" title="Dental consonant">dental</a> articulation. They are mostly alveolar in modern Chinese varieties.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBaxter199249_29-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBaxter199249-29"><span>[</span>27<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li id="cite_note-32"><b><a href="#cite_ref-32">^</a></b> The <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[ʐ]</span> initial occurs in only two words <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E4%BF%9F" class="extiw" title="wikt:俟">俟</a> and <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E6%BC%A6" class="extiw" title="wikt:漦">漦</a> in the <i>Qieyun</i>, and is merged with <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[dʐ]</span> in the later <i><a href="/wiki/Guangyun" title="Guangyun">Guangyun</a></i>. It is omitted in many reconstructions, and has no standard Chinese name.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBaxter199256.E2.80.9357.2C_206_31-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBaxter199256.E2.80.9357.2C_206-31"><span>[</span>28<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li id="cite_note-34"><b><a href="#cite_ref-34">^</a></b> The retroflex and palatal sibilants were treated as a single series in the later rhyme tables.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBaxter199254.E2.80.9355_33-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBaxter199254.E2.80.9355-33"><span>[</span>29<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li id="cite_note-dzr-36">^ <a href="#cite_ref-dzr_36-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-dzr_36-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> The initials 禪 and 船 are reversed from their positions in the rhyme tables, which are believed to have confused them.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBaxter199252.E2.80.9354_35-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBaxter199252.E2.80.9354-35"><span>[</span>30<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li id="cite_note-palatal-38">^ <a href="#cite_ref-palatal_38-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-palatal_38-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> In the rhyme tables, the palatal allophone of <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[ɣ]</span> (云) is combined with <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[j]</span> (以) as a single initial 喻.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBaxter199255.E2.80.9356.2C_59_37-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBaxter199255.E2.80.9356.2C_59-37"><span>[</span>31<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li id="cite_note-40"><b><a href="#cite_ref-40">^</a></b> The point of articulation of the fricatives is not clear, and varies between the modern varieties.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBaxter199258_39-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBaxter199258-39"><span>[</span>32<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li id="cite_note-46"><b><a href="#cite_ref-46">^</a></b> Karlgren originally postulated Old Chinese consonant clusters with <i>-l-</i> in such cases.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPulleyblank1962110.E2.80.93111_45-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPulleyblank1962110.E2.80.93111-45"><span>[</span>37<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li id="cite_note-48"><b><a href="#cite_ref-48">^</a></b> Middle Chinese forms are given in Li Fang-Kuei's revision of Karlgren's notation,<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTELi1974.E2.80.9375224.E2.80.93227_47-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTELi1974.E2.80.9375224.E2.80.93227-47"><span>[</span>38<span>]</span></a></sup> with minor simplifications suggested by <a href="#CITEREFCoblin1986">Coblin (1986)</a>, p. 9.</li>
<li id="cite_note-52"><b><a href="#cite_ref-52">^</a></b> Originally proposed as voiced and voiceless fricative initials in <a href="#CITEREFPulleyblank1962">Pulleyblank (1962)</a>, pp. 114–119.</li>
<li id="cite_note-66"><b><a href="#cite_ref-66">^</a></b> <a href="#CITEREFBaxterSagart2010">Baxter &amp; Sagart (2010)</a> derive the additional initials from two nasal prefixes, either of which can be fused or attached as a <a href="/wiki/Minor_syllable" title="Minor syllable">minor syllable</a>.</li>
<li id="cite_note-68"><b><a href="#cite_ref-68">^</a></b> Finals of divisions I, II and IV occurred only in rows 1, 2 and 4 of the rhyme tables respectively, while division III finals occurred in rows 2, 3 or 4 depending on the initial.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBaxter199264.2C_66.2C_67.2C_69_67-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBaxter199264.2C_66.2C_67.2C_69-67"><span>[</span>55<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li id="cite_note-73"><b><a href="#cite_ref-73">^</a></b> In their Middle Chinese reconstructions, Li and Baxter distinguish the <i>chongniu</i> by using <i>-ji-</i> as a purely notational device for III-4.<sup id="cite_ref-72" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-72"><span>[</span>59<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li id="cite_note-85"><b><a href="#cite_ref-85">^</a></b> <a href="/wiki/Chinese_language" title="Chinese language">Chinese</a>: <span lang="zh" xml:lang="zh">“四聲之辯，古人未有。”</span>, in Chen Di (1541–1617), <i>Mao Shi Gu Yin Kao</i> 《毛詩古音考》, quoted in <a href="#CITEREFWang2008">Wang (2008)</a>, p. 72.</li>
</ol>
</div>
